p since back in the 1990s, during the years when Wall Street banks financed=
 Trump=E2=80=99s casino misadventures. So there are no surprises in their r=
elationship at this point. Trump considered Marc as a possible director of =
the Office of Management and Budget during Trump I, after the latter had sp=
earheaded the creation of an institute at Wharton, both men=E2=80=99s alma =
mater, focused on good government and the federal budget. That became the P=
enn Wharton Budget Model, which scores all sorts of government-proposed pro=
grams, similarly to how the Congressional Budget Office scores proposals, o=
nly in a more broadly accessible way. In any event, the O.M.B. gig didn=E2=
=80=99t work out; at the time, Marc couldn=E2=80=99t easily disentangle him=
self from his various Apollo obligations and conflicts.<br/><br/>Eight year=
s later, for whatever reasons, Marc was
better able to make himself available. During their chat, Marc expressed hi=
s belief that there was a chance for =E2=80=9Cfundamental change,=E2=80=9D =
a chance to =E2=80=9Cdo everything you want to do, but do it in a smart way=
=2E=E2=80=9D Smart tariffs. Smart depor=
tation. =E2=80=9CYou can make this bet=
ter,=E2=80=9D Marc told him, according to someone familiar with that conver=
sation. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m rooting for you.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>In Marc=E2=
=80=99s view, the election offered a stark choice. In his mind, Trump=E2=80=
=99s return to the Oval Office was an =E2=80=9Cuncertain death,=E2=80=9D ye=
s, but it was far preferable to the =E2=80=9Ccertain death=E2=80=9D of elec=
ting <b>Kamala Harris</b>=E2=80=94the choice  between fear of change or fea=
r of more of the status quo, and for him, the <b>Biden</b>-Harris status qu=
o wasn=E2=80=99t working for the country. (It has worked for him personally=
, of course; he=E2=80=99s worth around $10 billion these days.) <br/></td>
